				 Heads roll, probe ordered

 OUR CORRESPONDENT
																								Brahmanigaon (Kondhmal), Dec. 28: The situation in this communally sensitive town continued to be tense even as chief minister Naveen Patnaik ordered a judicial probe into the clashes in the district and changed the collector.
																								In a related development, state steel amp; mines minister Padmanabha Behera, who represents Kondhmal district, resigned from cabinet owning moral responsibility for the communal situation. 
																								The central paramilitary forces today conducted a flag march in the volatile Darringibadi, Baliguda and Barakhamba areas, while the district police planned to extend the march in the peripheral areas, which witnessed an armed mob attack on a Hindu village yesterday, which led to a police firing and death of one person, said the Kondhmal superintendent of police, N. Bhol, who is camping here. 
																								Presently, four platoons of CRPF, two platoons of specially trained Special Operation Group and two platoons of state police force are patrolling the area, said the SP. 
																								Our efforts are on to restore confidence among the panic-stricken people of the area, who were attacked by an armed mob yesterday, he said. 
																								The SP confirmed that the police had to open fire to disperse the mob, which went on the rampage and one person succumbed to bullet injuries.
																								Meanwhile, Naveen Patnaik has ordered a judicial probe into the entire incident. Retired high court judge Basudev Panigrahi would conduct the inquiry into the circumstances that led to the incident. Malkangiri collector Manish Verma was appointed as the Kondhmal collector replacing B. Mohapatra.
																								Steel and mines minister Padmanabha Behera today sent his resignation to the chief minister. I resigned on my own. I take the moral responsibility for all that has happened, said Behera. 

